Love my flyhweel. Totally different feeling and really gets you strong:
Flywheels work by training the eccentric portion of the lift. 
Our muscles are stronger in the eccentric so they can handle a bigger load. Flywheels work by pulling down during the eccentric really hard, forcing you to try to stop that action. 

They have a totally unique feel and are unlike anything else in the gym!

Pan American Champion, 2023. Bariloche, Argentina. 114/158/172.

I was incredibly anxious about this meet. I don’t think people realize that it’s only my 2nd international meet ever! I had a total I needed to hit to secure funding AND it was my first Olympic qualifier. Also, I was still a little anxious to put heavy weights on the bar after getting hurt in July. 

I competed well - going 5/6 and sticking to the plan, hit the stipend total and get my feet wet again after not competing internationally since November 2021. I’m content and Wil and I have a plan for the rest of Olympic qualification. 

Bariloche has a very, very special place in my heart. It is one of the most beautiful places I’ve ever been. This week proved that I am stronger than I think - mentally, physically and emotionally. I mourned and celebrated the life of my friend, Brandon Penny and I competed on the same exact day my dad had a massive stroke, 3 years ago. Wil told me before my last attempt that “Joe’s daughter’s got this.” He read in a book that sometimes if you see yourself from someone’s eyes that you look up to, you can feel more confident or want to make them proud. I’d say it worked! 

I love you Brandon and I miss you already. I love you Dad, and can’t believe God blessed me with truly the best and strongest dad ever in the history of the world. 

Wil - Thank you for going on this wild journey with me. Thank you for being patient with me as I navigate the life of an athlete training for the Olympics. 

✌🏽out, Argentina. Up next - Cuba in June!!

Whoa! Bariloche, ARG will always be one of my favs.

A stressful barbell story 👀 

Thank you @barbellstories for capturing my session perfectly. 

Not everyday do you take 4 clean and jerk attempts due to a clock issue.

I usually do my best to stay calm and focused but sometimes our emotions get the best of us. We are all human. As I watch this video, I realize that even though my coach isn’t able to work with me on competition day, I know he is living in the moment with me. Just from the sidelines. If you are an athlete you understand what it is like to build a trusting relationship with your coach. You share the highs and lows together, and everything in between. All working towards a common goal. It is atypical to not have that follow through on competition day. Lucky for us, that day is only 1% of the days that we put in as a team on this journey. The other 99%, ‘behind the scenes work’, is equally (if not more) important. 

Here’s to becoming experts at this “sidelines” coaching thing. We are learning, and doing our best to adapt. At the end of the day, no one can lift the weight but me.

#barbell #story #emotions #competition #session #coach #snatch #cleanandjerk #teamcanada

One of the most frustrating things in weightlifting is 

👉🏽having the strength to pull the bar plenty high enough….

👉🏽having the strength to squat the bar up once you receive it…

🚫But not having the mobility to receive it in a good spot on the chest. 

That is a limitation in your front rack mobility and its really common in people new to weightlifting. 

Having good front rack mobility is essential to success in the lifts. If you are unable to find the right spot to receive the bar in the clean or hold the bar in a front squat you will be much more likely to miss a lift. 

More importantly you are at a much higher risk of injury or pain from these cleans and front squat if you don’t have the mobility to get it in the right place. 

If your wrists hurt everytime you clean or front squat, if your shoulders and upper back ache, those can be problems of lacking mobility in this position. 

Try adding in these 3 mobility exercises to improve your front rack positioning!

One of the most frustrating problems in weightlifting is a wimpy elbow on your snatches. 

In weightlifting the goal is to get the bar from the ground to the overhead position in a stylish and efficient way. One of the pieces of weightlifting which can be frustrating is getting the bar overhead but having a slight pressout when you try to lock it in overhead. 

Now the cause of a pressout is not actually what most people thing. 

It is not a lack of giant juiced up arm muscles like triceps and delts. So despite the fact that it’s your elbow bending…no amount of triceps pushdowns will improve that pressout. 

The most common cause of a pressout in the snatch is mis-timing the change of direction in the lift. 

In a good lift at the top of the second pull, around the hip,  the athlete extends their hips and knees up to get the bar moving at it’s maximum speed. This is a vertical movement to create vertical displacement of the barbell. 

Once that occurs the athlete leaves the ground momentarily and moves under the barbell. 

When a pressout occurs the athlete usually PULLS back on the bar too much and extends their shoulders behind the bar too much. This and a host of other errors can cause the bar to move horizontally too much. 
 When horizontal movement occurs the athlete will use bad strategies to get under and when they get under late, and do so in a horizontal…going from back to forward….they will pressout. 

#weightlifting #usaw #lifting #pressout #snatch #olylifting #1kilo #1kiloweightlifting

To be a good weightlifter we need to develop glutes and hamstrings for a variety of reasons. 

One of which is that they can help us lift more weight. 

When the bar reaches the hip position it is not only your quads that create upward propulsion of the bar, it is the action of hip extension  which is primarily controlled by the glutes and hammies. 

Secondly and more importantly, 

well developed posterior chain can help us be less likely to suffer from injuries,

 as weak hamstrings and glutes will often lead to compensatory patterns like over arching the bar when finishing the pull.

Seriously, the best lifts happen when the mind is calmest, uncluttered and free of distraction.

Don’t let your phone ruin your lift

Ready to have your mind blown? 

A 2014 study of restaurant service noted that trips to a popular New York restaurant are taking almost DOUBLE the time they did 10 years ago. 

The reason?

Smart Phones🤯🤳🏼

Asking waiter’s to take pictures of a group, taking pictures of your plate, posting to social media, and trying to find out the wi-fi password are all reasons that service time almost doubled since 2004.

The time we spend in and on our social media is ruining our ability

I know you don’t come here for the latest updates on the New York food scene, but bear with me, I’m going someplace.

Picture this, a “friend” of yours is going for a big lift. They’ve been on fire all day as they work up in weight.. hitting every weight along the way. 

Now they’re at a weight that would be a new PR.

So logically…have to wait on the perfect song in their headphones. 

Then take 5 minutes getting the perfect angle for their phone, balancing it on a foam roller with a dumbbell in front of it to prop it up like a Rube Goldberg contraption.

 I rarely see this work out well for a lifter. 🙅🏼‍♂️

I don’t make my lifters remove their phones from training unless I’m especially irritable, but seriously, checking Instagram, texts, Facebook, snapchat, TikTok and bumble between every lift isn’t a recipe for success.

Do use your phone for video, and then leave it alone👏🏽🎬

The best training occurs in the mind. 🧘🏼‍♀️

If your mind is a jumbled mess because of a near constant flow of information from your phone, you won’t be training well.

Do utilize the insane technology in your pocket to video your lifts and get some immediate feedback. 🤳🏼

When I started lifting 20 years ago, we would break out the video camera during training maybe 1x per month. 

Then we’d go pop it in the VCR (Google it) and watch it after training, then if we remembered we’d apply it the next time we were training. 

Obviously that process has sped up plenty today, and you can see yourself lift almost instantaneously. 😜
INCREASE YOUR BASELINE 🏋🏻‍♂️🙌🏽

Don’t “Go all meathead, unless you’re a meathead”

As a weightlifter the common imagery others have of how we compete is the slap in the face, yell, and scream, maybe even hit the nose torque that we’ve all probably seen on YouTube. 

I mean I saw a Lithuanian lifter do it once, so why don’t I do it.

While I never train in that way, I’m usually pretty quiet during training, I often thought that to “get to another level” I needed to call on my more meat-headed side to do so.

This strategy rarely worked.

I’d get slapped on the back and only think about how much the slap hurt, I’d yell and grunt and look like an old guy yelling and grunting. 

If you’re training has gone well up to a meet then more than likely your meet will go even better because of your taper and the adrenaline of competing.

 Literally no slaps are needed for you to feel better on meet day.

Olympic Weightlifting Mechanics Hierarchy - picked up from @wilfleming / @1kilo.wl

First: Shapes
Then: Speed
Finally: Load

When?
Learning or teaching Olympic weightlifting

What does this mean?
“First, we want to understand the positions or shapes that you need to achieve in the lifts so that you will have success.

What’s a rack position? What’s an overhead position? Etc. What do those positions look like and how do you move between them?

Next, move slowly between these positions to moving with some speed. Once the athlete can do that with some speed, now they’re recruiting bigger muscles, because speed requires bigger motor units.

NOW, we can add weight. Load is the final thing we need to worry about.

If you get those first two down (shapes and speed), load will come with no problem later on.” - @wilfleming / @1kilo.wl

AMERICAN OPEN FINALS RECAP!! 🏋🏼‍♀️✨

95kg / 116kg 211kg total 🙏🏼 4th overall

Holy moly what a freaking weekend. It takes a few days to really soak up all the feelings and emotions tied to your performances. I swear I learn something new about myself at each and every meet which is an awesome feelings since I’ve  been an athlete my whole life. 

This meet was definitely a special one. It was my 2nd appearance at the American Open Finals and I wanted to have a better experience than I did at the first one. With all the work I put in the last year I’m happy with the results that I received but not satisfied. I know I have alot more potential but I now have more things I can take to work on for future meets ahead. 

Last years Finals I opened up at 80kg/102kg… w/ no total. That hurt alot. But I knew something had to change and that was getting the quality coaching to help me advance further. Thats where I found @wilfleming & @1kilo.wl

Wil has taught me SO much about weightlifting, my technique, being an athlete and reminding me to always stay hungry but humble. 

This year I hit every single goal we had for the year. We wanted to hit a 95kg snatch and a 120kg clean and jerk, go to nationals and medal/podium and continue to feel WORTHY in a sport. 

Although that 120kg didnt make its comp debut, she did in training and will be seen in 2024. 

I finished out my 2023 season w/ a 211kg total ( 95kg snatch and 116kg)  and many many other training session PRs. 

- Other highlights from this meet: i opened 9kg heavier on my snatch and 14kg heavier on my clean and jerk that last year. So that just proves that good solid programming and quality coaching can take you to new heights. 

I’m very proud of my accomplishments and can’t wait to see what the next season brings! 

Thanks to everyone who has supported me along this journey I couldn’t do it without you! @solosnyder @dominikpolv @blackironnutrition @morganvoz @kieferlammi @alltru_hp @strengthbybond @thewellnessprojectlv_ @321podium

One of the most frustrating things in weightlifting is having the strength to pull the bar plenty high enough. 

Having the strength to squat the bar up once you receive it…

But not having the mobility to receive it in a good spot on the chest. 

That limitation is in your front rack mobility and its really common in people new to weightlifting. 

Having good front rack mobility is essential to success in the lifts. If you are unable to find the right spot to receive the bar in the clean or hold the bar in a front squat you will be much more likely to miss a lift. 

More importantly however you are at a much higher risk of injury or pain from these cleans and front squat if you don’t have the mobility to get it in the right place. 

If your wrists hurt everytime you clean or front squat, if your shoulders and upper back ache, those can be problems of lacking mobility in this position. 

My top solutions for increasing front rack mobility include: 

Increasing mobility in the lats, pecs, t-spine and wrists.
